topic.body:
In every new zite I make, I like to have both a `ZeroFrame.cmd` and `ZeroFrame.cmdp` available, the latter being exactly the same as `cmd` except it returns a promise once finished instead of requiring a callback.

Here is `cmdp` implemented in JS:

```
    cmdp(cmd, params={}) {
        return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
            this.cmd(cmd, params, (res) => {
                if (res && res.error) {
                    reject(res.error)
                } else {
                    resolve(res)
                }
            })
        })
    }
```

I assume https://github.com/HelloZeroNet/ZeroNet/blob/master/plugins/UiConfig/media/js/utils/ZeroFrame.coffee is the file we'd need to add this to, however I'm unfamiliar with coffeescript.

Consider the following example:

```
class ZeroApp extends ZeroFrame {
  onOpenWebsocket() {
    zeroframe.cmd("wrapperSetLocalStorage", {"score": 500}, null);
  }
}

zeroapp = new ZeroApp()
```

If one runs this, they get `TypeError: this.site_info is null`. That is because even though the Websocket has been opened, (I assume) the ZeroNet daemon has not yet returned `site_info` to the UiWrapper.

While this is just a toy example, I have run into problems with this on ZeroLSTN, often needing to use the following trick just to ensure `site_info` has been loaded before performing some tasks:

```
class ZeroApp extends ZeroFrame {
  onOpenWebsocket() {
    setTimeout(() => {
      zeroframe.cmd("wrapperSetLocalStorage", {"score": 500}, null);
    }, 50);
  }
}

zeroapp = new ZeroApp()
```

`site_info` was resolved, but we potentially lost a few ms in the process.

Is it possible to provide a `ready()` function, either one that can be overridden or one that is run when `site_info` has been retrieved. It could even work like the following:

```
const zeroframe = new ZeroFrame();

zeroframe.onReady = function() {
  console.log("Ready!");
}
```
